<br>
Nibs are going to give you better control over the thickness of your lines and tend to give your lines more energy, but it isn't any faster than using a Micron...and depending on what you're doing can actually take longer.  When you use a nib, you pretty much have to redip the pen every stroke, because you absolutely do not want to run out of ink in the middle of a line.  Dipping the nib isn't instantaneous, since you have to make sure that there isn't an ink blob waiting to fall off, so it is more time consuming than it may seem at first.  Also, ink from a Micron dries relatively quickly.  Ink from a nib takes much longer to dry, which can slow you down.<br>
<br>
Going to a nib is worthwhile, but if you're doing it to save time, chances are it won't. <p>=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=<br>
<a href="http://www.happysoda.com"><img src="http://www.happysoda.com/images/banner.jpg" border="1"></A>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Violent Femme</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/26/02 10:56:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4395.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth1.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: efficient inking?</span><hr size=1> Super Rats: Actually, a nib can hold quite a bit of inking, and having to continuously go back and dip the nib in ink really doesn't take that much time.  But I do believe they are faster than a micron because it's just one single and easy motion to vary your line width, whereas you have to go over the area several times with a micron.<br>
<br>
Spike:  If you're going to start brush inking, make sure you get a really good decent sable hair brush.  I bought one this summer that cost $20can, but it was totally worth it.  I picked it up rather easily actually, and I noticed a HUGE difference in my inks after the first page of sequentials.  I still keep my tech pens handy though.  They're still much better and faster for backgrounds.  It's really hard to use a brush with a ruler.  o_O <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
